ifeSummary":"Richard Monington于1430年出生在英国格盧斯特斯爾包特利。他于1454年与Ellen Walwyn在英国英格兰格盧斯特斯爾包特利结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他去世在法国皮卡迪索姆。"},"hr":{"1430–":"1430.–preminuo","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454.–preminuo","1455–1497":"1455.–1497","1430–Male":"1430.–preminuo","1426":"1426","1455":"1455.","1466":"1466","1454":"1454.","1497":"1497","1430":"1430.","1549":"1549","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Francuska"},"cs":{"1430–":"1430–Zesnulý","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454–Zesnulý","1455–1497":"1455–1497","1430–Male":"1430–Zesnulý","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1430":"1430","1549":"1549","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, Anglie","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Francie"},"da":{"1430–":"1430–Afdød","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454–Afdød","1455–1497":"1455–1497","1430–Male":"1430–Afdød","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1430":"1430","1549":"1549","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1430–":"1430–Overleden","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454–Overleden","1455–1497":"1455–1497","1430–Male":"1430–Overleden","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1430":"1430","1549":"1549","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1430–":"1430–Deceased","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454–Deceased","1455–1497":"1455–1497","1430–Male":"1430–Deceased","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1430":"1430","1549":"1549","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England","Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Monington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Monnington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Monnington","meanings":["English: locative name from Monnington on Wye or Monnington Straddle in Vowchurch (both Herefs)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":119,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Monington was born in 1430, in Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England. He married Ellen Walwyn in 1454, in Pauntley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1430–":"1430–Surnud","1426–1466":"1426–1466","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1455–1497":"1455–1497","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1430":"1430","1549":"1549","Pa